abstract = {Human Activity Recognition (HAR) stands as a pivotal technique in the pattern recognition community, devoted to deciphering human movements and actions by one or multiple sensory inputs. Given the ubiquitous and unobtrusive nature of WiFi signals, the use of Channel State Information (CSI) for invisible HAR perception has recently emerged as a significant research focus. In this paper, we introduce a attentional multi-scale dilated convolutional network(AMDCN) designed to facilitate non-line-of-sight WiFi-only action sensing from coarse to fine granularity by capturing continuous action sequences with corresponding localization across temporal and spatial streams. Acknowledging that the efficacy of WiFi signals can be significantly affected by environmental changes and varies across different sub-carriers, we develop an Action Temporal Decoder (ATD) aimed at interpreting actions based on contextual information derived from temporal channels. Furthermore, we construct an Action Spatial Decoder (ASD) tasked with identifying action positions informed by context from spatial channels. Comprehensive quantitative and qualitative evaluations have been conducted to validate our proposed methodologies.},
